<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-sec-quaternions" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Reduced trace and reduced norm in Quaternion algebra</title>
    <introduction>
        <p>
            In this section we define the trace and the norm of a quaternion. Throughout this section we assume that <m>F</m> is a field of characteristic not <m>2</m> and that <m>Q=(a,b)_F</m> is a quaternion algebra.
        </p>
    </introduction>
    <definition xml:id="def-trace-norm-quaternion">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>x=x_0+x_1i+x_2j+x_3k\in Q</m>. The <term>reduced trace</term> of <m>x</m> is <m>\Trd{Q}(x)=x+\gamma(x)</m> and the <term>reduced norm</term> of <m>x</m> is <m>\Nrd{Q}(x)=x\gamma(x)</m>, where <m>\gamma</m> is the canonical involution (see <xref ref="def-canonical-involution-on-quaternion"/>).
            </p>
        </statement>
    </definition>
    <lemma xml:id="lem-basic-properties-trace">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Suppose that <m>F</m> is a field of characteristic not <m>2</m> and that <m>Q=(a,b)_F</m> is a quaternion algebra.
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            For <m>x\in Q</m>, <m>\Trd{Q}(x)\in F</m>. In fact, if <m>x=x_0+x_1i+x_2j+x_3</m> then, <m>\Trd{Q}(x)=2x_0</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\Trd{Q}\colon Q\to F</m> is an <m>F</m>-linear map.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </lemma>
    <lemma xml:id="lem-basic-properties-norm">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Suppose that <m>F</m> is a field of characteristic not <m>2</m> and that <m>Q=(a,b)_F</m> is a quaternion algebra.
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            For <m>x\in Q</m>, we have <m>\Nrd{Q}(x)\in F</m>. In fact, if <m>x=x_0+x_1i+x_2j+x_3</m> then, <m>\Nrd{Q}(x)=x_0^2-ax_1^2-bx_2^2+abx_3^2</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\Nrd{Q}\colon Q\to F</m> is multiplicative, i.e., <m>\Nrd{Q}(xy)=\Nrd{Q}(x)\Nrd{Q}(y)</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            For <m>x\in Q</m>, we have <m>\Nrd{Q}(x)=\Nrd{Q}\left(\gamma(x)\right)</m>, i.e., <m>x\gamma(x)=\gamma(x)x</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            An element <m>x\in Q</m> is invertible if and only if <m>\Nrd{Q}(x)\neq 0</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </lemma>
    <exercise>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Show the following.
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>(-1,-1)_{\R}</m> and <m>(-1,-1)_{\Q}</m> are division algebras;
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>(-1,-1)_{\C}</m> is not a division algebra;
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>(1,b)_F</m> is not a division algebra.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </exercise>
    <lemma xml:id="lem-quadratic-equation-satisfied-by-quaternion">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>Q</m> be a quaternion algebra over a field <m>F</m> of characteristic <m>\neq 2</m>. Every <m>x\in Q</m> satisfy a quadratic polynomial over <m>F</m>, viz.,
                <me>
                    x^2-\Trd{Q}(x)x+\Nrd{Q}(x)=0.
                </me>
                
            </p>
        </statement>
    </lemma>
    <proof>
        <p>
            Indeed,
            <md>
                <mrow>x^2-\Trd{Q}(x)x+\Nrd{Q}(x) \amp = x^2-(x+\gamma(x))x+x\gamma(x)</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp = x^2-x^2-\gamma(x)x+x\gamma(x)</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp = 0.</mrow>
            </md>
        </p>
    </proof>
    <lemma xml:id="lem-matrix-of-left-multiplication">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Suppose that <m>F</m> is a field of characteristic not <m>2</m> and that <m>Q=(a,b)_F</m> is a quaternion algebra. Consider <m>q=x+yi+zj+wk\in Q</m>.
                The map <m>L_q\colon Q\to Q</m> given by <m>r\mapsto qr</m> is <m>F</m>-linear. If <m>[L_q]</m> is the matrix of <m>L_q</m> with respect to the basis <m>\{1,i,j,k\}</m> then,
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            the trace of the matrix <m>\left[L_q\right]</m>, <m>\tr\left[L_q\right]=2\Trd{Q}(q)</m>, and
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            the determinant of the matrix <m>\left[L_q\right]</m>, <m>\det\left[L_q\right]=\left(\Nrd{Q}(q)\right)^2</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </lemma>
    <proof>
        <p>
            We leave it to the reader to check that the map is <m>F</m>-linear, also see <xref ref="ex-regular-representation"/>. The following is the matrix of <m>L_q</m> with respect to the basis <m>\{1,i,j,k\}</m>.
            <me>
                \left[L_q\right]=\begin{pmatrix}x\amp ay\amp bz\amp -abw\\y\amp x\amp bw\amp -bz\\z\amp -aw\amp x\amp ay\\w\amp -z\amp y\amp x\end{pmatrix}
            </me>
            Thus, <m>\tr\left[L_q\right]=2\Trd{Q}(q)</m>. The determinant of the matrix is 
            <me>
                \det\left[L_q\right]=a^2b^2w^4+x^4+2abw^2x^2+a^2y^4-2a^2bw^2y^2-2ax^2y^2+b^2z^4-2ab^2w^2z^2-2bx^2z^2+2aby^2z^2.
            </me>
            One may verify that <m>\det\left[L_q\right]=\left(\Nrd{Q}(q)\right)^2</m>.
        </p>
    </proof>
</section>